      "text": "Your Guide to Rates | Con Edison\n\nSkip to Main Content\n\nYou are using an unsupported browser. Please download the latest version of Chrome, Firefox, Edge, or Safari.\n\nSelect a section What Are Rates and Tariffs? How They Work Your Rate Options Glossary of Terms\n\n## What Are Rates and Tariffs?\n\n### Rate\n\nA rate is what you pay for energy. It covers the price of what you use, the costs to build, maintain, and operate the infrastructure to deliver your energy, as well as taxes. It also includes paying the people who work 24/7 in all-weather to make sure you have safe, reliable service. If you get your energy from Con Edison, your rate also includes the supply price, which varies based on weather, demand, and market prices. We buy the energy you use in competitive markets and pass those costs on to you without making a profit.\n\n### Tariff\n\nA tariff is a schedule of the rates, terms, and conditions under which Con Edison provides electric, gas, and steam service. These tariffs are formal documents that must be filed with and approved by the New York State Public Service Commission (PSC).\n\n## How They Work\n\nCon Edison’s rates are set by the tariffs filed with the PSC, which regulates the state's electric, gas, and steam utilities and reviews and approves their rates and terms of service. Each rate varies based on factors like the amount of energy used, the time of day, and the season, and is measured in different units:\n\n- Electric in kilowatt-hours (kWh)\n- Gas in therms\n- Steam in thousands of pounds (Mlbs)\n\nYou can learn more about rates and tariffs through the following pages:\n\n- Electric Rates & Tariffs\n- Natural Gas Rates & Tariffs\n- Steam Rates & Tariffs\n\n## Your Rate Options\n\nFind the rate that's right for you.\n\nExpand all\n\nEV Phase-In Rates\n\nEV Phase-in rates are designed to support qualifying commercial customers operating EV chargers. They offer a transition toward demand-based delivery charges as commercial customers with EV chargers scale operations and manage bill impacts.\n\nElectric Vehicle Time-Of-Use Rate\n\nAllows you to switch your whole home to the time-of-use rate for one year with no risk. After you’ve been billed on the time-of-use for 12 months, we’ll compare what you paid under the time-of-use rate with what you would have paid under the standard residential rate. If you paid more, we’ll credit your account for the difference.\n\nSteady Use Rate\n\nSave by using large appliances and devices at different times (rather than all at once) and shifting energy use to off-peak hours. This plan may be a good fit if you are a residential customer using a heat pump to heat and/or cool your home and keep your thermostat at a steady temperature.\n\nSmart Energy Billing Plan\n\nSave by using large appliances and devices at different times (rather than all at once) and shifting energy use to off-peak hours when possible. For residential and non-residential customers (small business).\n\nStandby Rates\n\nStandby rate plans charge based on your electricity demand during set periods of each day. Rate plan options are available for residential, small business, and large business customers.\n\nTime-Of-Use Rates\n\nResidential customers, as well as small and large businesses, can pay less than the standard rate of electricity during certain times of the year with our Time-of-Use rate.\n\nAdditional Rates for Eligible Customers\n\nReligious institutions, veterans’ organizations, and some community residences have the choice of being billed under either residential or non-residential rates. This choice may be made separately for each service. Typically, residential electric rates are more economical, but commercial rates may benefit some customers.\n\nLEARN MORE ABOUT RESIDENTIAL RATES LEARN MORE ABOUT COMMERCIAL RATES\n\nFor more information, email us or call 1-800-752-6633.\n\n## Glossary of Terms\n\nWe want you to understand how your energy bill works. That’s why we’ve defined some of the more complicated terms you might see.\n\n## General Glossary\n\nExpand all\n\nActual vs. Estimated Read\n\nAn actual read is the exact amount of energy you used, recorded by your smart meter or, in rare cases, by a meter reader. An estimated read is a projection based on your past energy use when an actual read isn’t available.\n\nBasic Service Charge (or Customer Charge)\n\nA flat, monthly fee that helps maintain a safe and reliable energy delivery system, covering services like meter readings, billing, and customer support.\n\nBillable Demand vs. Contract Demand for Commercial Customers\n\nBillable Demand is the actual, highest amount of electricity a business uses during a specific time. This charge reflects the real-time load your business requires. Contract Demand is the maximum electricity (in kW) we agree to provide your business at any time.\n\nBudget Billing\n\nA service that estimates your energy use for the year and spreads the cost across 12 equal monthly payments to avoid seasonal spikes.\n\nNote: We review your account regularly and, if your energy use changes significantly, we may adjust your monthly payment amount.\n\nConsolidated Bill\n\nCombines supply charges from an ESCO with delivery charges into one bill for simplicity.\n\nESCO (Energy Service Company)\n\nA company that supplies electricity and natural gas to homes and businesses. Con Edison still delivers the energy and provides essential services.\n\nMerchant Function Charge\n\nCovers the cost of buying and selling electricity or natural gas in the wholesale market, including administrative costs.\n\nMonthly Rate Adjustment\n\nReflects changes in energy costs due to factors like weather, supply, and demand, ensuring you’re billed for the actual cost of energy.\n\nRetail Access Customer\n\nA customer who buys energy supply from an ESCO while Con Edison delivers the energy and provides essential services.\n\nStandby Service for Commercial Customers\n\nIf you generate your own electricity on-site, this service guarantees a reliable, uninterrupted power supply from our grid to back up your systems.\n\nSub-metering\n\nEnsures accurate billing for individual units in multi-unit buildings by using sub-meters.\n\nSystem Benefit Charge\n\nA state-mandated fee funding clean energy programs like energy efficiency initiatives and renewable energy projects.\n\nTaxes\n\nIncludes state and local taxes and surcharges on energy use and delivery services, which are passed on to the government.\n\nZone\n\nGeographic areas in Con Edison’s service territory where delivery costs vary due to local taxes and grid maintenance.\n\nShow More\n\n## Electric Glossary\n\nExpand all\n\nDemand Charge\n\nBased on the highest amount of electricity used at a single moment during a billing period, separate from regular energy charges.\n\nkW (Kilowatt) vs. kWh (Kilowatt-hour)\n\nA kilowatt measures the rate of electricity use at any moment, while a kilowatt-hour measures total electricity use over time.\n\nNYISO Load Zones\n\nEleven geographic areas (labeled A-K) covering Con Edison’s electric service area.\n\nPeak vs. Off-Peak Billing (or Time-of-Use Billing)\n\nElectricity costs more during peak times (weekdays) and less during off-peak times (nights, weekends, and certain holidays).\n\nSummer Billing Period\n\nElectricity costs more from June 1 to September 30 due to higher demand and production costs. Costs are lower during the rest of the year (October 1 to May 31).\n\n## Gas Glossary\n\nExpand all\n\nMonthly Rate Adjustment for Gas\n\nReflects changes in gas costs due to weather, supply, and demand, ensuring customers pay for the actual cost of gas used.\n\nTherm\n\nA unit of heat energy used to measure natural gas consumption for billing.\n\nWinter Billing Period\n\nGas costs are higher from November 1 to April 30 due to increased heating demand. Costs are lower during the rest of the year.\n\nTherm Zone\n\nA geographic area where gas bills are adjusted based on temperature data from a specific local weather station.\n\nMore About RatesLearn how rates affect your bill and discover programs designed to help you save. Go Now\n\nRate EnrollmentSelect or change to ",
